post_text:
Our Athletic Department announces that we have the go ahead to hold all fall sport contests beginning this week. There are stipulations and rules that we must follow. The most important is there will only be two spectators allowed per athlete. For each contest, the athlete (not parent) is to come to the athletic office, or middle school office for middle school athletes and give the names of their two spectators. Payment of $5 per spectator is required at the time of providing the names. Exact change or check is required. No general admission will be allowed at any event. Parents are not to call the athletic office to hold spots. Face coverings are required at all events.

For those not able to attend we will have information coming soon about the possibility of streaming some athletic events.

Updated sport schedules will be posted on our athletic website at www.grasslakewarriors.com soon. With all the changes due to COVID, we are in the process of solidifying dates.

post_text:
Beginning Monday, August 24, road repairs will begin on Michigan Avenue in Grass Lake from the west Village limits to the east Village limits, as well as on N. Union Street from Michigan Avenue to the north Village limits. Milling of the top layer of asphalt will occur followed by repaving. They expect the project to continue for 3-4 days. There will be flag men on this project. At this time we understand that traffic will still be able to navigate through the area, but with occasional stoppages. We have been encouraged to bypass the area when feasible.

This construction was originally scheduled to occur earlier, but contractor scheduling was conflicted. The Jackson County Department of Transportation is working with our busing schedules to reduce delays as much as possible.

post_text: We are so proud of Grass Lake students Addison and Avery Nowaczck for their entrepreneurial spirit and their giving nature that provided support for a dog kennel for homeless dogs. Well done Ladies!
shared_text:
Mikey & Me
August 19 at 6:31 PM ·

Good evening everyone,

Recently I received an email from one of our Facebook followers, Kelli Nowaczck. She explained that her two daughters, Addison (age 11) and Avery (age 9) had been hosting lemonade stands this summer, while being mindful of the COVID-19 crisis. They told me they wanted to donate their earnings to help the homeless dogs at the Mikey & Me kennels. 😉

So I invited them out for an afternoon visit last week and Addison and Avery were able to spend time interacting with our current residents. 🐶 They then presented me with $100.00 they had raised at their lemonade stands this summer. The girls explained that some of their customers had rounded up their bill when they advised them that the proceeds would be used to benefit homeless dogs.

Thank you Addison and Avery for your selfless act of kindness. I know that hosting a customer-based fundraiser this summer had to be difficult and I am so very proud of your accomplishment.

Please enjoy these photos of Addison and Avery’s visit last week.

Dan DePew
Mikey & Me

Important News from the Kitchens at Grass Lake Community Schools regarding SchoolPay.

We appreciate all of you that have created a new account with SchoolPay (formerly PaySchools) for the upcoming school year 2020-2021 lunch program. Please don't be discouraged if your student is showing a zero balance at this time. Our Food Service has its own POS program called MealMagic and all of your funds are still safe in your account or your student's account. SchoolPay is our secondary deposit and lunch fund information program. At this time it is still in its transition and import stage. You can continue to create your new accounts while all the bugs are being worked out.

Thank you and we are looking forward to seeing your students and their happy faces!

Sincerely,
Kelly Bolton
Food Service Director
Grass Lake Schools
kelly.bolton@grasslakeschools.com
517-867-5597

All payment balances that are currently in our system will remain in your accounts and active through this transition.

post_text: Sincere appreciation goes out to Eagle Scout candidate and 2020 GLHS graduate Samantha Kohls for completing a major repair on our ticket booth at Howard Stoker Memorial Field. The project was to repaint the exterior building and put a new roof on it. Fighting through multiple hornets' nests, she cleared those out and sealed the gaps on the overhang to prevent them from returning. Along with replacing the roof and fascia, and completing a paint job, Samantha made us very proud with the prominent additions of our "GL" logo. It is beautiful. Thank you Samantha!

The Michigan College Access Network (MCAN) has awarded $51,816 in its eighth round of COVID-19 Response Grants to seven organizations in Michigan, of which Grass Lake High School received $2,300. The MCAN grants help Michigan high schools support emergent postsecondary projects and programs in their communities.

The funding sources for the Grass Lake High School grant were $1,550 from the Michigan College Access Network, and
$750 from the Jackson Community Foundation

Grass Lake High School used its grant to support a virtual celebration of College Decision Day 2020 for graduating seniors.

post_text:
Attention GLHS Class of 2020 Graduating seniors and parents:

Recently, Mrs. King was notified that she received a grant for "Senior Decision Day". With that money she is ordering Decision Day banners to be displayed at Graduation on August 8th! After graduation the students can keep their banners.

Mrs. King needs to order these quickly so that they will be here in time. An email was sent about two weeks ago that resulted in only approximately 40 students. This is seniors last chance to have a banner at graduation.

Please contact Mrs. King by email (kim.king@grasslakeschools.com) stating that you would like to move ahead with a banner, and include a photo of yourself with the highest resolution possible. (Past photos are not available.) Please also respond to let her know that you are not interested in a banner

The final order will be placed next week, but it takes time to design each banner. If you never responded to Mrs. King's Decision Day email, please contact her by email at kim.king@grasslakeschools.com to finalize this project by Monday July 27!

We appreciate your support!
text:
Attention GLHS Class of 2020 Graduating seniors and parents:

Recently, Mrs. King was notified that she received a grant for "Senior Decision Day". With that money she is ordering Decision Day banners to be displayed at Graduation on August 8th! After graduation the students can keep their banners.

Mrs. King needs to order these quickly so that they will be here in time. An email was sent about two weeks ago that resulted in only approximately 40 students. This is seniors last chance to have a banner at graduation.

Please contact Mrs. King by email (kim.king@grasslakeschools.com) stating that you would like to move ahead with a banner, and include a photo of yourself with the highest resolution possible. (Past photos are not available.) Please also respond to let her know that you are not interested in a banner

The final order will be placed next week, but it takes time to design each banner. If you never responded to Mrs. King's Decision Day email, please contact her by email at kim.king@grasslakeschools.com to finalize this project by Monday July 27!

We appreciate your support!

Rob Kellerman‎Grass Lake Jr. High Football - 2020
July 16 at 4:29 PM ·

Time for summer workouts to begin!

We will begin our summer workouts on Monday, July 20th. We will be working out with the High School teams this year, at least for the first few weeks, from 7:00-8:00pm on the practice field behind the High School.

All players will be required to answer COVID-19 related survey questions upon arrival. Players temperature is to be taken at home prior to coming to workouts. If the players temperature is 100.3° or higher, they may not participate and should NOT come to workouts.

Players should come see Coach Lape, Coach Poley, or myself upon arrival. Don’t get there more than 10 minutes prior. Players must bring their own water. Water will not be provided.…

BUS DRIVERS NEEDED -

Grass Lake Community Schools is in need of three bus drivers for the 2020-2021 school year. These are part-time positions working 6:15 AM-7:45 AM, and 2:45 PM-4:15 PM, being paid $45.31 per day for handling our morning and afternoon student bus runs. These positions also have optional additional income opportunities with extra-run field trips.

No experience is necessary. Certifications and training are paid for by us. Vision insurance is provided. If interested in discussing the possibilities, contact Doug Moeckel at 517-867-5544, or doug.moeckel@grasslakeschools.com.

PLEASE NOTE: If you find that you are interested in only doing morning or afternoon runs, call us. We would like to talk to you.

Scott Bray shared a post to the group: Grass Lake Open Forum.
June 16 at 3:30 PM ·

With the ceasing of publication of The Grass Lake Times, this is good news.

Scott Bray
June 16 at 3:29 PM ·

The Exponent in Brooklyn, who used to actually print The Grass Lake Times, has decided to start covering Grass Lake news. The Township has moved our legal notices to them. They are dedicating a reporter, Christine MacIntyre, to cover Grass Lake news and events. I encourage you to consider subscribing. Its $50 for a year, once a week. I also encourage the various groups to send her your news and events. We need community input to make it work. Newspapers are vital to the community. She agreed to allow me to share her contact info to jump start the process. Text or call: 517-581-0312 Email christine.m.macintyre@gmail.com

Important Survey for Grass Lake Parents/Caregivers -

Coming off of a unique completion of the 2019-2020 school year that included online learning, and with the uncertainty of how the start of the 2020-2021 school year will begin, the administrative team at Grass Lake Community Schools is requesting that our families complete a 3-minute survey found at https://bit.ly/2Uw0CR2 to allow us to evaluate your preferences toward how your child will receive their instruction this fall. Please complete the survey as quickly as possible, as the information will be invaluable for our planning during these uncertain times. Thank you!

If a family requires a paper survey to be sent to them, please have them call 517-867-5544 and leave their name and address, and a survey will be mailed to them.

post_text:
Well, that's a wrap. The 2019-2020 school year has officially come to an end and will be remembered for many years. Through this difficult time, our students, our families, and our staff have performed brilliantly as you have adapted to a new form of instruction that allowed our students to continue their learning while we await our return to "normal". Thank you all for your effort and cooperation throughout the past two months. You all rock!

Pictured are scenes from our George Long Elementary School good-bye parade with our students. Typically this scene would include bus loads of students waving to their teachers before their final bus ride home for the school year. Thank you to our caregivers for participating in this event and for allowing our teachers one last opportunity to see their students who they have missed so much. More photos are forthcoming.

We wish all of you a safe and happy summer as our administrators continue to plan for the 2020-2021 school year during the months to come to provide a positive educational environment for our students.

post_text: Along with commemorating our outgoing 5th grade class (the GLHS Class of 2027), this tree marks the retirement of long-time Grass Lake teacher Mrs. Patti Muto. Mrs. Muto has been a Grass Lake main-stay for many years; seeing change after change after change in instruction, and rolling through it with grace and professionalism. Generations of Grass Lake students can recount Mrs. Muto's kind disposition and supportive nature. We all will miss her very much. Thank you, Patti, for your dedication. (Pictured with Mrs. Muto are colleagues l-r: Mrs. Clark, Mrs. Dentel, Mrs. Bullock, Mrs. Muto, and Mrs. Deedler.)

With the announcement of Executive Order No. 2020-110, our playgrounds at George Long Elementary School are open again under the following guidelines:
Outdoor social gatherings and events among persons not part of a single household are permitted, but only to the extent that:
(a) The gathering or event does not exceed 100 people, and
(b) People not part of the same household maintain six feet of distance from one another.

PREVENTION TIPS
In addition to washing hands regularly and not touching your face, officials recommend practicing social distancing, assuming anyone may be carrying the virus.

Use disinfecting wipes or disinfecting spray cleaners on frequently-touched surfaces and carry hand sanitizer with you when you go into public places that include multiple hand touches.

ABC Training and Testing
May 28 at 2:08 PM ·

A few UPDATES that may answer some frequently asked questions:

We are FINALLY able to do CDL Training and Testing. NO CARS/MOTORCYCLES

During the Stay-Home Order, We CANNOT do any driving tests for a regular driver's license, nor can we do any motorcycle testing. We will resume testing on 6/13. You may call us to schedule an appointment, but it will be on or after 6/13.

We CANNOT do any Driver Education at this time; not In-person OR Online. All of our classes have either been cancelled or postponed, including our classes that were scheduled to begin June 8. We do not have any answers as to when we can resume. When the State allows driver education to resume, we will then need to hear from our schools to see if/when we are allowed in their buildings this summer. When we get everything in line, we will be sure to notify the students who have already pre-registered.

If you have any questions, feel free to call 517-563-2005.

On Monday, May 25, we will observe Memorial Day, which is a federal holiday in the United States for honoring and mourning the military personnel who have died while serving in the United States Armed Forces.

Grass Lake observances will begin at Grass Lake's Memorial Park at 10 AM, and will be streamed on Facebook at https://www.facebook.com/groups/529596137206601/. Memorial Park services will be followed by a processional to the West Cemetery where deceased veterans' names will be announced.

If individuals wish to participate in the service, you are asked to socially distance and be respectful of others.

post_text:
Two messages for our Grass Lake Community Schools families....

1. On Monday, May 18, we will be sharing important information regarding the return of school-issued electronic devices, as well as information regarding the pickup of personal items that were left in school lockers when our students left school on March 13. CORRECTION: GRASS LAKE HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS WILL BE RECEIVING END-OF-YEAR INFORMATION ON WEDNESDAY, MAY 20. We apologize for any confusion this may have caused.

2. A reminder to our families picking up and dropping off homework at Grass Lake High School to please call the High School office on Mondays or Tuesdays to make an appointment for Wednesday pickups and drop offs. This scheduling is important for maintaining a safe, efficient, and orderly process for the transfer of school work. We appreciate your cooperation.

shared_text:
Grass Lake Warriors Youth Tackle Football
May 12 at 6:07 PM ·

2020 Youth Football

As we are all trying to navigate life through these difficult times I hope everyone has stayed safe and healthy.

With that said there is some changes that will affect some of our future players. First the 5th and 6th grade will remain tackle football. Second our 4th grade will play the 2020 season as tackle but the 4th graders for the 2021 season will be transitioning to travel flag football going forward. Third our 3rd graders for this year will be moved to travel flag football. We are following recommendations from the MHSAA and the league we participate in.

If there is any questions at all please contact Brent Jones either by phone 517-795-9712 or email warrioryouthfootball@yahoo.com

Lastly please email me your players information so I can start to get a head count.

Go Warriors!!!!

Grass Lake Community Wellness Initiative
May 4 at 10:12 AM ·

Reaching out to share information on an exciting opportunity!

1. Hospital First Responders and Essential Workers letter writing campaign –

With the help of our local organizations and faith communities, we created an easy process for community members to thank our hospital essential workers at St. Joe’s/Chelsea and Henry Ford Allegiance hospitals. We hope you will help to share the information. We hope you will write a thank you letter. We have 4 drop boxes and a link to make it easier for folks who are more spread out in our rural communities. To send an electronic letter, go to https://bit.ly/2xIT45h.

Please take a look at the plant list below to help limit the amount of time spent browsing the sale. Thank you so much for your support and we look forward to helping you with your garden needs next week!

post_text:
Mrs. Pam Broderick getting it done online for her "littles". The following was shared by Christy Broderick......

Happy World Book Day!

Because of today and what we’re currently going through, I wanted to honor my mom (“Ms. Pam”) and all of the other educators out there who are educating and reading virtually to their students. My mom and her co-teacher are making the best with what they have and are ensuring that their kiddos are still involved, even though they aren’t physically at school.

Reading to your child is super important 💕 To this day, I still love to hear my mom read stories; this is how I got to where I’m at today (working at a library and being a part of story times with young readers). She makes reading fun and this is why I enjoyed it tremendously growing up! It just goes to show you that even though we’re all going through uncertain times, reading will still bring us all together (virtually) 📚

#worldbookday #readingbringsustogether #educatorsrock

April 10 at 10:22 PM ·

With school now being held "in home" rather than "in house" for the remainder of the school year, the PTO has decided to cancel the Spring Warrior Wear sale. We will pick back up in the Fall. Perhaps some of you will be disappointed with having to wait, but I am sure many will be glad to see money that you thought you had spent, return now to your pocketbooks.

It doesn't feel right to fundraise for the PTO when there are so many more urgent monetary needs right now in our community. If you submitted a check or cash to us and have not had it returned, you will see it soon.

Stay well. Stay safe!!
